ional name of Norman origin, from any of the five places called Ouilly in Calvados, France."]},{"name":"Dilley","meanings":["English: possibly a pet form of an unrecorded Old English personal name <i>Dylla</i>, found as the first element in the placenames Dillington (in the former Huntingdonshire) and Dilton (in Wiltshire). The name may sometimes have been confused with   Doyley   and   Dolley   (see   Olley  ).","German: variant of   Dilly   or a surname of French origin, an altered form of   Delay  .","In some cases also an altered form of French   Dilly  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice D'Oyley was born in 1120, in Hook Norton, Oxfordshire, England. She married Ernulf De Mandeville in 1145, in Hook Norton, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1165, in Wallingford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1120–1165":"1120–1165","1120–1178":"1120–1178","1146–Male":"1146–Surnud","1149–1251":"1149–1251","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","abt 1149":"umbes 1149","1149":"1149","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1146":"1146","1145":"114